-- Crude Options Volatility Slips to Lowest Level in 11 Days
-- B y   B a r b a r a   P o w e l l
-- 2013-08-02T20:55:34Z
-- http://www.bloomberg.com/news/2013-08-02/crude-options-volatility-slips-to-lowest-level-in-11-days.html
Crude options volatility fell to an
11-day low as underlying futures declined.  Implied volatility for at-the-money options expiring in
September was 20.46 percent on the  New York Mercantile Exchange 
at 3:50 p.m., down from 21.79 yesterday.  West Texas Intermediate crude for September delivery fell
95 cents, or 0.9 percent, to settle $106.94 a barrel on the
Nymex. Prices increased 2.1 percent this week.  The most active options in electronic trading today were
September $113 calls, which fell 16 cents to 16 cents a barrel
on volume of 3,969 lots traded as of 4:18 p.m. September $114
calls were the second-most active, falling 13 cents to 10 cents
on volume of 2,445 contracts.  Calls accounted for 56 percent of electronic trading
volume. In the prior session, bearish bets made up 54 percent of
210,020 contracts exchanged.  September $100 puts were the most-active options yesterday
with 11,585 contracts changing hands as they fell 29 cents to 12
cents a barrel. December $90 puts fell 33 cents to 95 cents on
7,582 lots.  Open interest was highest for December $80 puts, with
38,206 contracts. Next were December $90 puts with 37,621 lots
and December $70 puts with 34,003.  The exchange distributes real-time data for electronic
trading and releases information the next business day on open-outcry volume, where the bulk of options activity occurs.  To contact the reporter on this story:
